{"title_page": "Eastern States Union", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \n|conventional_long_name =Eastern States Union  \n|common_name =Eastern States Union  \n|nation = the [[Dominion of India]]\n|subdivision = Union of [[princely state]]s\n|era = \n|capital =[[Raipur]]\n|year_start = 1947\n|date_start = \n|event_start= [[Independence of India]]\n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= Failure of the union\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =Eastern States Agency\n|s1 = Bihar\n|s2 = Orissa\n|s3 = Madhya Pradesh\n|flag_p1 = British Raj Red Ensign.svg\n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|flag_s2 = Flag of India.svg\n|flag_s3 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_coat = \n|image_map =\n|image_map_caption = \n|stat_area1 =\n|stat_year1 =\n|stat_pop1 =\n|footnotes = \n|today     = [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Odisha]] and [[Jharkhand]]\n}}\nThe '''Eastern States Union''' was a short-lived (1947\u201348) union of [[princely states]] in newly-independent [[India]] that gathered most of the princely states of the former [[Orissa Tributary States]] and [[Chhattisgarh States Agency]] in order to fill the vacuum of power created after the departure of the British and the wrapping up of the [[British Raj]].<ref>Schwartzberg, Joseph E., ed.: ''A Historical Atlas of South Asia'', 2. A., New York/Oxford 1992, {{ISBN|0-19-506869-6}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Rajkumar College Raipur.jpg|thumb|The [[Rajkumar College, Raipur]], the place of foundation of the Eastern States Union]]\n=== Creation ===\nThe union was formed right after the British Parliament decided to grant independence to [[India]] and [[Pakistan]] on 15 August 1947, following which the princely states became ''de facto'' independent as well.<ref>[[Ramachandra Guha]], ''[[India after Gandhi]]: The History of the World's Largest Democracy.'' HarperCollins, 2007</ref> In the transitional period the provincial [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] governments refused assistance to the princely states for they were hostile to the traditional princes and in fact were involved in popular agitations against them. In face of the situation of insecurity and continuous disturbances of the public order, the rulers of the states of the former [[Eastern States Agency]] formally founded the Eastern States Union in the [[Rajkumar College, Raipur|Raj Kumar College]] building in [[Raipur]]. The goal was to establish a unit that would be large enough to exist as a state within the Indian Union,<ref>Frederick George Bailey, ''Politics and Social Change: Orissa in 1959''. p. 179</ref> as well as to share the cost of maintenance of an adequate security and military force in order to restore law and order.<ref>Sadhna Sharma ed. ''States Politics in India'', 1995, p. 273</ref>\n\n=== Institutions ===\n{{Princely states topics}}\nThe Eastern States Union had a Premier, a Chief Secretary, a joint police force and a [[court of appeal]], but it had no legislature. The union selected [[Raipur]] as its capital and quickly took the cause of building a dam on the [[Indravati River]] in [[Kalahandi]].<ref>[http://kddfonline.com/2010/04/05/aftermath-of-merger-of-princely-states-in-orissa/ Aftermath of Merger of Princely States in Orissa]</ref> However, some of the larger states such as [[Mayurbhanj State|Mayurbhanj]] and [[Bastar State|Bastar]], as well as some minor ones, opted not to join the common effort.\n \n=== Demise and successor states ===\nIn the end the Eastern States Union proved an administrative failure and, following intense [[Praja Mandal]] movement agitations in [[Hindol State|Hindol]],  [[Nilagiri|Nilgiri]], [[Dhenkanal, India|Dhenkanal]] and [[Talcher]] in December 1947, it was dissolved early in 1948.<ref>D. P. Mishra, ''People's Revolt in Orissa: A Study of Talcher'', p. 185</ref>\n \nThe states that had formed the union then became part of the newly established states of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], [[Bihar]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].\n\nFollowing the demise of the Eastern States Union the states that became part of Orissa (now [[Odisha]]) were [[Gangpur State|Gangpur]], [[Bonai State|Bonai]], [[Bamra]], [[Keonjhar State|Keonjhar]], [[Rairakhol State|Rairakhol]], [[Sonepur State|Sonepur]], [[Athmallik State|Athmallik]], [[Pal Lahara State|Pal Lahara]], [[Talcher State|Talcher]], [[Patna State|Patna]], [[Baudh State|Baudh]], [[Dhenkanal State|Dhenkanal]], [[Hindol State|Hindol]], [[Daspalla State|Daspalla]], [[Narsinghpur State|Narsinghpur]], [[Baramba State|Baramba]], [[Athgarh State|Athgarh]], [[Tigiria State|Tigiria]], [[Nayagarh State|Nayagarh]], [[Ranpur State|Ranpur]] and [[Kalahandi State|Kalahandi]].\n \n[[Kharsawan State|Kharsawan]] and [[Saraikela State|Seraikela]], joined [[Bihar]] in May 1948.\n\nThe states that became part of Madhya Pradesh were [[Changbhakar State|Changbhakar]], [[Koriya State|Koriya]], [[Surguja State|Surguja]], [[Jashpur State|Jashpur]], [[Udaipur State, Chhattisgarh|Udaipur]], [[Raigarh State|Raigarh]], [[Sarangarh State|Sarangarh]], [[Kawardha State|Kawardha]], [[Khairagarh State|Khairagarh]], [[Nandgaon State|Nandgaon]] and [[Kanker State|Kanker]]. Since 2000 most of the areas of the former princely states in eastern Madhya Pradesh belong to the state of [[Chhattisgarh]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Princely states of the Eastern States Agency}}\n{{coord|21.2405|81.6138|type:edu_region:IN-CG|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Former states and territories of India]]\n[[Category:1940s in Orissa]]\n[[Category:History of Madhya Pradesh (1947\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:History of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:1948 disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \n|conventional_long_name =Eastern States Union  \n|common_name =Eastern States Union  \n|nation = the [[Dominion of India]]\n|subdivision = Union of [[princely state]]s\n|era = \n|capital =[[Raipur]]\n|year_start = 1947\n|date_start = \n|event_start= [[Independence of India]]\n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= Failure of the union\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =Eastern States Agency\n|s1 = Bihar\n|s2 = Orissa\n|s3 = Madhya Pradesh\n|flag_p1 = British Raj Red Ensign.svg\n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|flag_s2 = Flag of India.svg\n|flag_s3 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_coat = \n|image_map =\n|image_map_caption = \n|stat_area1 =\n|stat_year1 =\n|stat_pop1 =\n|footnotes = \n|today     = [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Odisha]] and [[Jharkhand]]\n}}\nThe '''Eastern States Union''' was a short-lived (1947\u201348) union of [[princely states]] in newly-independent [[India]] that gathered most of the princely states of the former [[Orissa Tributary States]] and [[Chhattisgarh States Agency]] in order to fill the vacuum of power created after the departure of the British and the wrapping up of the [[British Raj]].<ref>Schwartzberg, Joseph E., ed.: ''A Historical Atlas of South Asia'', 2. A., New York/Oxford 1992, {{ISBN|0-19-506869-6}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Rajkumar College Raipur.jpg|thumb|The [[Rajkumar College, Raipur]], the place of foundation of the Eastern States Union]]\n=== Creation ===\nThe union was formed right after the British Parliament decided to grant independence to [[India]] and [[Pakistan]] on 15 August 1947, following which the princely states became ''de facto'' independent as well.<ref>[[Ramachandra Guha]], ''[[India after Gandhi]]: The History of the World's Largest Democracy.'' HarperCollins, 2007</ref> In the transitional period the provincial [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] governments refused assistance to the princely states for they were hostile to the traditional princes and in fact were involved in popular agitations against them. In face of the situation of insecurity and continuous disturbances of the public order, the rulers of the states of the former [[Eastern States Agency]] formally founded the Eastern States Union in the [[Rajkumar College, Raipur|Raj Kumar College]] building in [[Raipur]]. The goal was to establish a unit that would be large enough to exist as a state within the [[Indian Union]],<ref>Frederick George Bailey, ''Politics and Social Change: Orissa in 1959''. p. 179</ref> as well as to share the cost of maintenance of an adequate security and military force in order to restore law and order.<ref>Sadhna Sharma ed. ''States Politics in India'', 1995, p. 273</ref>\n\n=== Institutions ===\n{{Princely states topics}}\nThe Eastern States Union had a Premier, a Chief Secretary, a joint police force and a [[court of appeal]], but it had no legislature. The union selected [[Raipur]] as its capital and quickly took the cause of building a dam on the [[Indravati River]] in [[Kalahandi]].<ref>[http://kddfonline.com/2010/04/05/aftermath-of-merger-of-princely-states-in-orissa/ Aftermath of Merger of Princely States in Orissa]</ref> However, some of the larger states such as [[Mayurbhanj State|Mayurbhanj]] and [[Bastar State|Bastar]], as well as some minor ones, opted not to join the common effort.\n \n=== Demise and successor states ===\nIn the end the Eastern States Union proved an administrative failure and, following intense [[Praja Mandal]] movement agitations in [[Hindol State|Hindol]],  [[Nilagiri|Nilgiri]], [[Dhenkanal, India|Dhenkanal]] and [[Talcher]] in December 1947, it was dissolved early in 1948.<ref>D. P. Mishra, ''People's Revolt in Orissa: A Study of Talcher'', p. 185</ref>\n \nThe states that had formed the union then became part of the newly established states of [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], [[Bihar]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].\n\nFollowing the demise of the Eastern States Union the states that became part of Orissa (now [[Odisha]]) were [[Gangpur State|Gangpur]], [[Bonai State|Bonai]], [[Bamra]], [[Keonjhar State|Keonjhar]], [[Rairakhol State|Rairakhol]], [[Sonepur State|Sonepur]], [[Athmallik State|Athmallik]], [[Pal Lahara State|Pal Lahara]], [[Talcher State|Talcher]], [[Patna State|Patna]], [[Baudh State|Baudh]], [[Dhenkanal State|Dhenkanal]], [[Hindol State|Hindol]], [[Daspalla State|Daspalla]], [[Narsinghpur State|Narsinghpur]], [[Baramba State|Baramba]], [[Athgarh State|Athgarh]], [[Tigiria State|Tigiria]], [[Nayagarh State|Nayagarh]], [[Ranpur State|Ranpur]] and [[Kalahandi State|Kalahandi]].\n \n[[Kharsawan State|Kharsawan]] and [[Saraikela State|Seraikela]], joined [[Bihar]] in May 1948.\n\nThe states that became part of Madhya Pradesh were [[Changbhakar State|Changbhakar]], [[Koriya State|Koriya]], [[Surguja State|Surguja]], [[Jashpur State|Jashpur]], [[Udaipur State, Chhattisgarh|Udaipur]], [[Raigarh State|Raigarh]], [[Sarangarh State|Sarangarh]], [[Kawardha State|Kawardha]], [[Khairagarh State|Khairagarh]], [[Nandgaon State|Nandgaon]] and [[Kanker State|Kanker]]. Since 2000 most of the areas of the former princely states in eastern Madhya Pradesh belong to the state of [[Chhattisgarh]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Princely states of the Eastern States Agency}}\n{{coord|21.2405|81.6138|type:edu_region:IN-CG|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Former states and territories of India]]\n[[Category:1940s in Orissa]]\n[[Category:History of Madhya Pradesh (1947\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:History of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:1948 disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n", "name_user": "DrKay", "label": "safe", "comment": "linked in preceding sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_States_Union"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Cooper", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish-Filipina film actress, vaudeville dancer, and singer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Philippine name|Rosario|Cooper}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elizabeth Cooper\n| birth_name         = Isabel Rosario Cooper\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|1|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manila]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1960|6|29|1914|1|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], [[U.S.]]\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Cooper'''<ref name=Karnow>{{cite-Karnow|Isabel Rosario Cooper}}</ref> (born '''Isabel Rosario Cooper'''; January 15, 1914 &ndash; June 29, 1960)<ref>Dates cited in ''California Death Index'', accessed 23 May 2011.</ref> was a [[Philippines|Filipina]] [[film]] [[actress]], [[vaudeville]] dancer, and singer. In addition to her brief movie career, Cooper was also known for being the mistress of [[General]] [[Douglas MacArthur]].\n\nBorn in [[Manila]], she was infamous for the first on-screen kiss in a [[Filipino women|Filipino]] movie, ''[[Ang Tatlong Hambog]]'' (1926). In 1930, she met US General [[Douglas MacArthur]] and became his [[mistress (lover)|mistress]]. He arranged for her to follow him to [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nWhile serving as Army Chief of Staff in the 1930s, MacArthur filed a libel action against a journalist at ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]]. When Pearson added Cooper to his list of witnesses to be deposed, MacArthur dropped the suit. MacArthur subsequently paid Cooper $15,000 to leave Washington, the money allegedly delivered by his aide, [[Dwight Eisenhower]]. However, she did not return to the Philippines, and after a few failed attempts in Hollywood and a hair dressing shop in the Midwest, committed suicide in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tragic love stories in Philippine history|url=http://www.filipiknow.net/tragic-love-stories-in-philippine-history/|website=filipiknow.net|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nElizabeth was born '''Isabel Rosario Cooper''' to a Scottish father Arthur Edmund Cooper and Rosario Lopez Chinese-Filipina mother, who was a [[Hacienda Luisita|haciendera]] (farm owner) from [[Vallehermoso, Negros Oriental|Vallehermoso]], [[Negros Oriental]]. She was nicknamed \"Dimples\". As a teenager she traveled Southeast Asia as a [[Torch song|torch singer]] / entertainer.\n\n==Film career==\nIsabel appeared in a few B-grade Filipino films starting in 1925, under the screen name \"Chabing\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalisay|first1=Butch|title=Pinoys on the Potomac|url=http://www.philstar.com/arts-and-culture/2014/11/24/1394625/pinoys-potomac|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=Philstar|date=21 November 2014}}</ref> Two of her films were ''Miracles of Love'' (1925) and ''Ang Tatlong Hambog'' (1926). In the latter film, Cooper made [[Cinema of the Philippines|Philippine film]] history with [[Luis Tuason]] when they performed the very first kissing scene in a Philippine film. She was 12 years old at the time.\n\nShe did not act in any Filipino films after 1930, although the 1941 Tagalog film ''[[Ikaw Pala]]'' is sometimes wrongly attributed to her. \"Ikaw Pala\" had another actress named Cresencia Aligada acting in it in a supporting role; Aligada also went by the screen name \"Dimples,\" hence the mistaken identity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Santos|first1=Simon|title=Rare pre-war Tagalog movie posters|url=http://video48.blogspot.co.uk/2011/02/rare-pre-war-tagalog-movie-flyers-29.html|website=Video 48|publisher=Simon Santos|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter her 1934 break-up with MacArthur, Cooper attempted to find roles in Hollywood, but in vain.\n\n==Relationship with General MacArthur==\n\nIn 1930, at the age of 16, Cooper met the American [[General Douglas MacArthur]], then commander of all U.S. troops in the [[Philippines]]. MacArthur's marriage had ended a year earlier. Cooper became his mistress in Manila, a fact the 50-year-old MacArthur hid from his 80-year-old mother.<ref name=\"Karnow\"/> In Manila, the teenaged Cooper lived in [[Paco, Manila|Paco]].\n\nFive months after they first met, MacArthur returned to the United States; while he intended to bring her to Washington, he could not risk scandal by traveling with her, so he bought her a ticket on a ship to arrive after him. She arrived in Washington and ended up ensconced in an apartment in [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]], Washington, D.C. MacArthur later moved her to the Chastleton Hotel (now a co-op building). According to one biographer of MacArthur, [[William Manchester]], MacArthur ''\"showered [Cooper] with presents and bought her many lacy tea gowns, but no raincoat. She didn't need one, he told her; her duty lay in bed.\"''\n\nIn 1933, when the secret affair threatened to become public, MacArthur brought it to an end, reportedly giving her $15,000 and a ticket back to the Philippines. She did not use the ticket and never returned to the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web |first=David W. |last=Lutz |url=http://isme.tamu.edu/JSCOPE97/Lutz97.htm |title=The Exercise of Military Judgment: A Philosophical Investigation of the Virtues and Vices of General Douglas MacArthur |website=JSCOPE 97 |publisher=Joint Services Conference on Professional Ethics |date=31 January 1997}}</ref> In 1934, the 20-year-old Cooper moved to the [[Midwestern United States]], where she owned a hairdressing salon, before moving to [[Los Angeles]] several years later.\n\nCooper tried to find work as an actress in [[Hollywood]]; however, the only roles that she could manage were those as an extra, such as a geisha and a Filipina nurse in films, and in such other films as ''[[Anna and the King]]'' (as one of Rex Harrison's concubines in the first 1946, b&w film screen version of the Anna-King of Siam tale) and ''[[Squaw]]''.<ref>{{IMDb name |id=0178104 |name=Dimples Cooper}}. Retrieved November 25, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCooper committed suicide by [[Barbiturate overdose|overdosing on barbiturates]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite book |last=Yeatter |first=Bryan L. |year=2007 |title=Cinema of the Philippines: A History and Filmography, 1897-2005 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=V6saAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Elizabeth+Cooper%22+overdose&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=barbiturates |publisher=McFarland & Company |page=16 |isbn=9780786430475}}</ref> She was 46 years old.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Manchester |first1=William |authorlink1=William Manchester |title=[[American Caesar: Douglas MacArthur, 1880-1964]] |date=Sep 30, 1978 |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=9780316544986}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* 1925 ''Miracles of Love''\n* 1926 ''[[Ang Tatlong Hambog]]''\n* 1927 ''Fate or Consequence''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Manchester |first1=William |authorlink1=William Manchester |title=[[American Caesar: Douglas MacArthur, 1880-1964]] |date=Sep 30, 1978 |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=9780316544986}}\n* {{cite book |last= Garcia|first= Jessie B.|title= A Movie Album Quizbook|year= 2004|publisher= Erehwon Books & Magazine|location= Iloilo City, Philippines |isbn= 971-93297-0-X|pages= 78\u201380, 127}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name |id=0178104 |name=Dimples Cooper}}\n\n{{Douglas MacArthur}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino actresses who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Douglas MacArthur]]\n[[Category:Drug-related suicides in California]]\n[[Category:Barbiturates-related deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Filipino film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Manila]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Filipino actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish-Filipina film actress, vaudeville dancer, and singer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Philippine name|Rosario|Cooper}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Elizabeth Cooper\n| birth_name         = Isabel Rosario Cooper\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|1|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manila]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1960|6|29|1914|1|15}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], [[U.S.]]\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Cooper'''<ref name=Karnow>{{cite-Karnow|Isabel Rosario Cooper}}</ref> (born '''Isabel Rosario Cooper'''; January 15, 1914 &ndash; June 29, 1960)<ref>Dates cited in ''California Death Index'', accessed 23 May 2011.</ref> was a [[Philippines|Filipina]] [[film]] [[actress]], [[vaudeville]] dancer, and singer. In addition to her brief movie career, Cooper was also known for being the mistress of [[General]] [[Douglas MacArthur]].\n\nBorn in [[Manila]], she was infamous for the first on-screen kiss in a [[Filipino women|Filipino]] movie, ''[[Ang Tatlong Hambog]]'' (1926). In 1930, she met US General [[Douglas MacArthur]] and became his [[mistress (lover)|mistress]]. He arranged for her to follow him to [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\nWhile serving as Army Chief of Staff in the 1930s, MacArthur filed a libel action against a journalist at ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]]. When Pearson added Cooper to his list of witnesses to be deposed, MacArthur dropped the suit. MacArthur subsequently paid Cooper $15,000 to leave Washington, the money allegedly delivered by his aide, [[Dwight Eisenhower]]. However, she did not return to the Philippines, and after a few failed attempts in Hollywood and a hair dressing shop in the Midwest, committed suicide in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tragic love stories in Philippine history|url=http://www.filipiknow.net/tragic-love-stories-in-philippine-history/|website=filipiknow.net|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nElizabeth was born '''Isabel Rosario Cooper''' to a Scottish father Arthur Edmund Cooper and Rosario Lopez Chinese-Filipina mother, who was a [[Hacienda Luisita|haciendera]] (farm owner) from [[Vallehermoso, Negros Oriental|Vallehermoso]], [[Negros Oriental]]. She was nicknamed \"Dimples\". As a teenager she traveled Southeast Asia as a [[Torch song|torch singer]] / entertainer.\n\n==Film career==\nIsabel appeared in a few B-grade Filipino films starting in 1925, under the screen name \"Chabing\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalisay|first1=Butch|title=Pinoys on the Potomac|url=http://www.philstar.com/arts-and-culture/2014/11/24/1394625/pinoys-potomac|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=Philstar|date=21 November 2014}}</ref> Two of her films were ''Miracles of Love'' (1925) and ''Ang Tatlong Hambog'' (1926). In the latter film, Cooper made [[Cinema of the Philippines|Philippine film]] history with [[Luis Tuason]] when they performed the very first kissing scene in a Philippine film. She was 12 years old at the time.\n\nShe did not act in any Filipino films after 1930, although the 1941 Tagalog film ''[[Ikaw Pala]]'' is sometimes wrongly attributed to her. \"Ikaw Pala\" had another actress named Cresencia Aligada acting in it in a supporting role; Aligada also went by the screen name \"Dimples,\" hence the mistaken identity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Santos|first1=Simon|title=Rare pre-war Tagalog movie posters|url=http://video48.blogspot.co.uk/2011/02/rare-pre-war-tagalog-movie-flyers-29.html|website=Video 48|publisher=Simon Santos|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter her 1934 break-up with MacArthur, Cooper attempted to find roles in Hollywood, but in vain.\n\n==Relationship with General MacArthur==\n\nIn 1930, at the age of 16, Cooper met the American [[General Douglas MacArthur]], then commander of all U.S. troops in the [[Philippines]]. MacArthur's marriage had ended a year earlier. Cooper became his mistress in Manila, a fact the 50-year-old MacArthur hid from his 80-year-old mother.<ref name=\"Karnow\"/> In Manila, the teenaged Cooper lived in [[Paco, Manila|Paco]].\n\nFive months after they first met, MacArthur returned to the United States; while he intended to bring her to Washington, he could not risk scandal by traveling with her, so he bought her a ticket on a ship to arrive after him. She arrived in Washington and ended up ensconced in an apartment in [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]], Washington, D.C. MacArthur later moved her to the Chastleton Hotel (now a co-op building). According to one biographer of MacArthur, [[William Manchester]], MacArthur ''\"showered [Cooper] with presents and bought her many lacy tea gowns, but no raincoat. She didn't need one, he told her; her duty lay in bed.\"''\n\nIn 1933, when the secret affair threatened to become public, MacArthur brought it to an end, reportedly giving her $15,000 and a ticket back to the Philippines. She did not use the ticket and never returned to the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web |first=David W. |last=Lutz |url=http://isme.tamu.edu/JSCOPE97/Lutz97.htm |title=The Exercise of Military Judgment: A Philosophical Investigation of the Virtues and Vices of General Douglas MacArthur |website=JSCOPE 97 |publisher=Joint Services Conference on Professional Ethics |date=31 January 1997}}</ref> In 1934, the 20-year-old Cooper moved to the [[Midwestern United States]], where she owned a hairdressing salon, before moving to [[Los Angeles]] several years later.\n\nCooper tried to find work as an actress in [[Hollywood]]; however, the only roles that she could manage were those as an extra, such as a geisha and a Filipina nurse in films such as ''[[The King and I]]'' and ''[[Squaw]]''.<ref>{{IMDb name |id=0178104 |name=Dimples Cooper}}. Retrieved November 25, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nCooper committed suicide by [[Barbiturate overdose|overdosing on barbiturates]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite book |last=Yeatter |first=Bryan L. |year=2007 |title=Cinema of the Philippines: A History and Filmography, 1897-2005 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=V6saAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Elizabeth+Cooper%22+overdose&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=barbiturates |publisher=McFarland & Company |page=16 |isbn=9780786430475}}</ref> She was 46 years old.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Manchester |first1=William |authorlink1=William Manchester |title=[[American Caesar: Douglas MacArthur, 1880-1964]] |date=Sep 30, 1978 |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=9780316544986}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* 1925 ''Miracles of Love''\n* 1926 ''[[Ang Tatlong Hambog]]''\n* 1927 ''Fate or Consequence''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Manchester |first1=William |authorlink1=William Manchester |title=[[American Caesar: Douglas MacArthur, 1880-1964]] |date=Sep 30, 1978 |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=9780316544986}}\n* {{cite book |last= Garcia|first= Jessie B.|title= A Movie Album Quizbook|year= 2004|publisher= Erehwon Books & Magazine|location= Iloilo City, Philippines |isbn= 971-93297-0-X|pages= 78\u201380, 127}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name |id=0178104 |name=Dimples Cooper}}\n\n{{Douglas MacArthur}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino actresses who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Douglas MacArthur]]\n[[Category:Drug-related suicides in California]]\n[[Category:Barbiturates-related deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Filipino film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Manila]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Filipino actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)]]\n", "name_user": "Conphucius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelationship with General MacArthur", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Cooper"}
{"title_page": "Ceybil Jefferies", "text_new": "'''Ceybil Jefferies''', also known by the [[stage name]] '''Sweet Sable''', (death announced April 10, 2020) was an American [[house music|house]] and [[R&B]] [[vocalist]] and musician best known for her work during the 1990s, including the 1996 [[Netherlands|Dutch]] house single, \"[[It's Gonna Be Alright (Deep Zone song)|It's Gonna Be Alright]]\" with Deep Zone, which hit No. 20 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> Her other best known singles included \"So Special\" and \"Open Your Heart\",  both of which reached the Top 20 of the Billboard [[Dance Club Songs]] charts in 1991.<ref name=vibe>{{cite news |first=Desire |last=Thompson |title=Vocalist Ceybil Jefferies, Also Known As Sweet Sable, Has Died From Coronavirus |url=https://www.vibe.com/2020/04/vocalist-ceybil-jefferies-sweet-sable-died-from-coronavirus-obituary |work=[[Vibe (magazine)]]  |publisher= |date=2020-04-13 |accessdate=2020-04-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420064955/https://www.vibe.com/2020/04/vocalist-ceybil-jefferies-sweet-sable-died-from-coronavirus-obituary |archivedate=2020-04-20 |url-status=live}}</ref> Jefferies, who sometimes went by the [[stage name]] Sweet Sable beginning in 1994, often changed the spelling of her name or reinvented it, depending on the release.<ref name=vibe/> Variations of her name included '''Ceybil''', '''Sable Jefferies''', her birthname '''Sybil Jefferies''', and '''Ceybil Jeffries'''.<ref name=vibe/>\n\nJefferies should not be confused with [[Sybil (singer)|Sybil]], another American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[pop music|pop]] [[singing|singer\u2013songwriter]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn '''Sybil Jefferies''', she was a native of [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=vibe/> \n\nShe initially signed with [[Atlantic Records]], which released her debut album, ''Let Music Take Control'', in 1991.<ref name=vibe/> Two singles from the album, \"So Special\" and \"Open Your Heart\", peaked as hits in the Top 20 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts that same year.<ref name=vibe/> \n\nPrior to the release of her sophomore album, ''Open Your Heart'', Jefferies left Atlantic Records and signed with [[Scotti Brothers Records]] under the new artist name \"Sable Jefferies.\"<ref name=vibe/> Her first single from \"Open Your Heart\", called \"Friends (For Old Time Sake)\", was more heavily influenced by the [[New jack swing]] genre, rather than her earlier house music work.<ref name=vibe/> \"Friends (For Old Time Sake)\" proved successful by reaching Number 15 on the [[Billboard R&B charts]] and reaching Number 2 on the Billboard [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> Only [[Doug E. Fresh]]'s single \"Freaks\" kept Jefferies' song from reaching the Number 1 spot on the Bubbling Under chart.<ref name=vibe/> Shortened to \"Old Time's Sake\", her song was included on ''[[Above the Rim (soundtrack)|Above the Rim]]'' film soundtrack in 1994 under her moniker, Sweet Sable.<ref name=revolt/> \n\nThe album also spawned two other singles, \"Tonight\" and \"Love Thang\", which both landed on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Billboard R&B chart]]. Her single, \"Love Than\", reached Number 1 on the former Billboard Hot Dance Breakdowns Chart in 1995, beating out [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]'s \"[[Think of You (Usher song)|Think of You]]\", which peaked at Number 2 behind Jefferies' song.<ref name=vibe/>\n\nIn 1996, she teamed with a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] house group called Deep Zone to provide vocals for their single, \"[[It's Gonna Be Alright (Deep Zone song)|It's Gonna Be Alright]]\" under her original name, Ceybil Jefferies. \"It's Gonna Be Alright\" peaked at Number 20 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> In a review written at the time, [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described the song as \"a joyfully optimistic romp merging edgy house beats with keyboards that are, by turns, jazzy and [[retro-disco]]. Life in the urban lane has done wonders for Jefferies' voice, which is now far more assured and smooth.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_xwsEAAAAMBAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_xwsEAAAAMBAJ/page/n24 25]|quote=deep zone it's gonna be alright chart.|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=5 August 1995|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nJefferies continued to record and release music into the 2000s. However, she was diagnosed with [[neurosarcoidosis]], an inflammatory type of [[sarcoidosis]] which severely affected her [[lungs]] and breathing capacity.<ref name=vibe/> Her diagnosis effectively ended her singing career.<ref name=vibe/> Additionally, Jefferies lost much of her [[visual perception|vision]] due to the illness.<ref name=vibe/><ref name=revolt/>\n\nCeybil Jefferies died from [[COVID-19]] in April 2020. Her death was announced and confirmed by music industry colleagues on April 10, 2020, including record producer [[Salaam Remi]].<ref name=vibe/><ref name=revolt>{{cite news |first=Tamantha |last=Gunn |title=Ceybil Jefferies reportedly passes away due to complications from Coronavirus |url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/4/14/21221214/ceybil-jefferies-passes-away |work=[[Revolt (TV network)]]  |publisher= |date=2020-04-14 |accessdate=2020-04-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424235538/https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/4/14/21221214/ceybil-jefferies-passes-away |archivedate=2020-04-25 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jefferies, Ceybil}}\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American house musicians]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ceybil Jefferies''', also known by the [[stage name]] '''Sweet Sable''', (death announced April 10, 2020) was an American [[house music|house]] and [[R&B]] [[vocalist]] and musician best known for her work during the 1990s, including the 1996 [[Netherlands|Dutch]] house single, \"[[It's Gonna Be Alright (Deep Zone song)|It's Gonna Be Alright]]\" with Deep Zone, which hit No. 20 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> Her other best known singles included \"So Special\" and \"Open Your Heart\",  both of which reached the Top 20 of the Billboard [[Dance Club Songs]] charts in 1991.<ref name=vibe>{{cite news |first=Desire |last=Thompson |title=Vocalist Ceybil Jefferies, Also Known As Sweet Sable, Has Died From Coronavirus |url=https://www.vibe.com/2020/04/vocalist-ceybil-jefferies-sweet-sable-died-from-coronavirus-obituary |work=[[Vibe (magazine)]]  |publisher= |date=2020-04-13 |accessdate=2020-04-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420064955/https://www.vibe.com/2020/04/vocalist-ceybil-jefferies-sweet-sable-died-from-coronavirus-obituary |archivedate=2020-04-20 |url-status=live}}</ref> Jefferies, who sometimes went by the [[stage name]] Sweet Sable beginning in 1994, often changed the spelling of her name or reinvented it, depending on the release.<ref name=vibe/> Variations of her name included '''Ceybil''', '''Sable Jefferies''', her birthname '''Sybil Jefferies''', and '''Ceybil Jeffries'''.<ref name=vibe/>\n\nJefferies should not be confused with [[Sybil (singer)|Sybil]], another American [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[pop music|pop]] [[singing|singer\u2013songwriter]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn '''Sybil Jefferies''', she was a native of [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=vibe/> \n\nShe initially signed with [[Atlantic Records]], which released her debut album, ''Let Music Take Control'', in 1991.<ref name=vibe/> Two singles from the album, \"So Special\" and \"Open Your Heart\", peaked as hits in the Top 20 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts that same year.<ref name=vibe/> \n\nPrior to the release of her sophomore album, ''Open Your Heart'', Jefferies left Atlantic Records and signed with [[Scotti Brothers Records]] under the new artist name \"Sable Jefferies.\"<ref name=vibe/> Her first single from \"Open Your Heart\", called \"Friends (For Old Time Sake)\", was more heavily influenced by the [[New jack swing]] genre, rather than her earlier house music work.<ref name=vibe/> \"Friends (For Old Time Sake)\" proved successful by reaching Number 15 on the [[Billboard R&B charts]] and reaching Number 2 on the Billboard [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> Only [[Doug E. Fresh]]'s single \"Freaks\" kept Jefferies' song from reaching the Number 1 spot on the Bubbling Under chart.<ref name=vibe/> Shortened to \"Old Time's Sake\", her song was included on ''[[Above the Rim (soundtrack)|Above the Rim]]'' film soundtrack in 1994 under her moniker, Sweet Sable.<ref name=revolt/> \n\nThe album also spawned two other singles, \"Tonight\" and \"Love Thang\", which both landed on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Billboard R&B chart]]. Her single, \"Love Than\", reached Number 1 on the former Billboard Hot Dance Breakdowns Chart in 1995, beating out [[Usher]]'s \"[[Think of You (Usher song)|Think of You]]\", which peaked at Number 2 behind Jefferies' song.<ref name=vibe/>\n\nIn 1996, she teamed with a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] house group called Deep Zone to provide vocals for their single, \"[[It's Gonna Be Alright (Deep Zone song)|It's Gonna Be Alright]]\" under her original name, Ceybil Jefferies. \"It's Gonna Be Alright\" peaked at Number 20 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Dance Club Songs]] charts.<ref name=vibe/> In a review written at the time, [[Larry Flick]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' described the song as \"a joyfully optimistic romp merging edgy house beats with keyboards that are, by turns, jazzy and [[retro-disco]]. Life in the urban lane has done wonders for Jefferies' voice, which is now far more assured and smooth.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_xwsEAAAAMBAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_xwsEAAAAMBAJ/page/n24 25]|quote=deep zone it's gonna be alright chart.|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=5 August 1995|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nJefferies continued to record and release music into the 2000s. However, she was diagnosed with [[neurosarcoidosis]], an inflammatory type of [[sarcoidosis]] which severely affected her [[lungs]] and breathing capacity.<ref name=vibe/> Her diagnosis effectively ended her singing career.<ref name=vibe/> Additionally, Jefferies lost much of her [[vision]] due to the illness.<ref name=vibe/><ref name=revolt/>\n\nCeybil Jefferies died from [[COVID-19]] in April 2020. Her death was announced and confirmed by music industry colleagues on April 10, 2020, including record producer [[Salaam Remi]].<ref name=vibe/><ref name=revolt>{{cite news |first=Tamantha |last=Gunn |title=Ceybil Jefferies reportedly passes away due to complications from Coronavirus |url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/4/14/21221214/ceybil-jefferies-passes-away |work=[[Revolt (TV network)]]  |publisher= |date=2020-04-14 |accessdate=2020-04-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424235538/https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/4/14/21221214/ceybil-jefferies-passes-away |archivedate=2020-04-25 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jefferies, Ceybil}}\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American house musicians]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Usher\u2192Usher (musician),vision\u2192visual perception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceybil_Jefferies"}
{"title_page": "Focal-JMLab", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n|brands         = Focal\n|name           = Focal-JMLab\n|logo           = [[File:Logo Focal ListenBeyond Noir 280px.jpg|latest Focal logo]]\n|type           = \n|founder        = Jacques Mahul\n|foundation     = 1979\n|hq_location_city = [[Saint-Etienne]], [[France]]\n|key_people     = Jacques Mahul - chairman and managing director\n|industry       = [[Consumer electronics]]\n|products       = [[home audio]], [[mobile audio]], [[professional audio]]\n|parent         = Vervent Audio Group\n|revenue        = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 110 million <small>(2019<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web | url=https://stereo-magazine.com/article/change-of-ownership-at-focal-naim | title=Change of ownership at Focal-Naim| date=2019-11-11}}</ref>)\n|num_employees  = 230<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.whathifi.com/features/focal-and-naim-french-anglo-alliance-thats-paying-dividends | title=Home}}</ref>\n|assets         = Naxicap Partners, Aquasour\u00e7a, Garibaldi Participations, Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Managers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hifiplus.com/articles/audios-transfer-window/|title=Audio\u2019s transfer window|website=Hi-Fi+}}</ref>\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.focal.com}}\n}}\n[[file:Focal JM lab opal 19ti crop.jpg|thumb|Focal Opal 19ti]]\n'''Focal-JMlab''' is a French brand, which has been designing and selling high-fidelity audio systems since 1979. This [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]]-based company manufactures [[Loudspeaker enclosure|loudspeakers]] for the home, [[Loudspeaker|speaker drivers]] for automobiles, [[headphones]] and professional monitoring loudspeakers.\n\nThe Grande Utopia is the brand's emblematic loudspeaker, which earned the company its worldwide reputation.<ref>[http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 Jack English auditions the JMlab Grand Utopia loudspeaker] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202120/http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |date=2013-10-29 }}, on ''focal.com''.</ref> It is considered one of the best high-fidelity loudspeakers in the world.<ref>[http://www.on-mag.fr/index.php/topaudio/actualites-news/10943-top-44-des-meilleures-enceintes-acoustiques-audiophiles-de-tous-les-temps-par-audiophilereviewcom Pierre Stemmelin, Top 44 des meilleures enceintes acoustiques audiophiles de tous les temps], on ''on-mag.fr/index.php''.</ref><ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307 Val\u00e9rie Marchive, Grande Utopia EM, l\u2019enceinte de tous les superlatifs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610205119/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307 |date=2015-06-10 }}, on ''lepoint.fr''.</ref>\n\nFocal's industrial strategy concentrates on having full control over the entire production process, from the design and manufacturing of the speaker drivers to the assembly of the final product. Its products are entirely designed and developed in France, and most of the production is carried out at the factory in Saint-\u00c9tienne (France).\n\nFocal-JMlab generates a \u20ac53 million annual turnover and employs about 230 people<ref name=\"auto1\"/> at its facility in Saint-\u00c9tienne, which groups the production, R&D and management departments at the same site. Its export share is 70%.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1980s ===\nFocal-JMlab, a research office dedicated to acoustics was founded in 1979 in Paris by engineer, high-fidelity enthusiast and technology journalist Jacques Mahul.<ref>[http://www.lexpress.fr/informations/vie-economique_642117.html Philippe Bidalon, \u00ab Les 100 qui font bouger Saint-\u00c9tienne : Jacques Mahul \u00bb], on lexpress.fr, ''[[L'Express]]''</ref> He began making his first speaker drivers in a small workshop in Saint-Etienne, at a precision mechanics company, which belonged to his father. Whilst producing his speaker drivers, Jacques Mahul also launched his own range of loudspeakers under the brand JMlab. His first loudspeaker, the DB13, was a bookshelf loudspeaker, which produced volumes comparable to larger loudspeakers, particularly in bass frequencies. Initially, he only sold his product to acquaintances but the DB13 was soon launched on the market.\n\nIn the 1980s, the two brands became established. Focal focused on innovation, producing specialised products such as the polyglass \"V\" cone and polykevlar cone. The materials used on the [[tweeter]] evolved from glass fibres to [[Kevlar]], producing a more linear frequency response curve and a smoother and less piercing treble.\nAs for JMlab, the company went from being a manufacturer of small-and medium-sized loudspeakers to a manufacturer of veritable high-end models.\n\n=== 1990s ===\nThings rapidly began to pick up speed in 1990 with the arrival of G\u00e9rard Chr\u00e9tien, another high end high fidelity enthusiast and [[editor-in-chief]] of the magazine ''L\u2019Audiophile'' since 1977. Currently, he is the managing director and marketing director of Focal-JMlab. By adapting the company's products to the demands of the consumer, the brand soon earned its role as leader on the French loudspeaker market.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/focal-jmlab-le-son-chez-soi-et-au-volant.N34160|title=Focal-JMlab Le son, chez soi et au volant|journal=Usinenouvelle.com/|first=L'Usine|last=Nouvelle|date=19 June 2003}}</ref> The company's turnover increased from \u20ac9 million in 1992 to \u20ac26 million in 2000.<ref name=\"pr\u00e9sentation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4022|title=Pr\u00e9sentation Focal-JMlab 2011, on the company official website|publisher=|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt was also in the early 1990s that the company implemented an export strategy for its loudspeakers across Europe, Southeast Asia and North America. The brand's reputation on the international stage was reinforced by various awards. The JMlab Vega model was voted \"Loudspeaker of the Year, 1992\" in Japan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audiomarketing.com.au/pdf/focal/history.pdf|title=History Focal, on audiomarketing.com|publisher=|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105154002/http://www.audiomarketing.com.au/pdf/focal/history.pdf|archive-date=2012-01-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 1996, the Grande Utopia model was praised by the international press.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |title=Jack English auditions the JMlab Grand Utopia loudspeaker, on ''Stereophile'' |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202120/http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\nFrom 2002, production was relocated in Saint-Etienne where about three-quarters of production still takes place with the aim of equipping every loudspeaker with \"Made in France\" speaker drivers.\n\nIn 2003, the two brands were incorporated under the name Focal-JMlab for home products, before being renamed as just Focal in 2005 for all product sectors.\n\n2003 was also the year that the company began collaborating with Paris-based design agency Pineau & Le Porcher. By combining sound quality and aesthetics, this move made Focal-JMlab products lifestyle loudspeakers in their own right and also gave the company a brand signature. Thus, Focal and Pineau & Le Porcher worked in close collaboration to come up with a completely new design for various ranges: Profile and Electra (2005), Chorus (2006), Utopia (2008) and Dome (2009).<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/quand-le-design-permet-de-se-differencier.N118371|title=Quand le design permet de se diff\u00e9rencier|first=L'Usine|last=Nouvelle|date=October 1, 2009|via=www.usinenouvelle.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the company bought up the Guy HF cabinet-making facility located in Bourbon-Lancy, Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire.\n\n=== 2010s ===\nIn 2011, Focal-JMlab merged with [[Naim Audio|Naim Audio Limited]], the leading high-end electronics brand in the UK, which mainly designs and manufactures audio electronics. The new holding company, Vervent Audio Group, owns and manages the two brands. However, both brands remain independent with their own specific philosophies and their own respective ranges and products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.on-mag.fr/index.php/topaudio/actualites-news/10577-focal-et-naim-audio-annoncent-leur-fusion-au-sein-de-lentite-focal-a-co|title=Focal et Naim Audio annoncent leur fusion au sein de l'entit\u00e9 Focal & Co|first=Pierre|last=Stemmelin|website=www.on-mag.fr}}</ref>\n\nThe two companies began consolidating their activities in 2013, with their presence on a common stand at the High End Show in Munich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908090919/http://www.hificritic.com/downloads/Munich2013.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 8, 2013|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Focal adopted a new visual identity and finally, in 2012, built a showroom and a new auditorium at its site in Saint-\u00c9tienne.\n\nIn 2014, Focal&Naim Group was taken over by its management team, Naxicap Partners (major shareholder), Aquasourca and Garibaldi Participations. Jacques Mahul remains involved and becomes Focal-JMlab Vice-Pr\u00e9sident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hifiplus.com/articles/audios-transfer-window/,|title=Why a week of audio business upheaval might not be a bad thing, on ''www.hifiplus.com''}}</ref> The same year, Focal is recognized by the French state thanks to ''The Entreprise du Patrimoine Vivant'' (Living Heritage Company) label. A label delivered under the authority of the French Minister for Economy, Finances and Industry rewarding French firms for the excellence of their traditional and industrial skills<ref>[http://www.patrimoine-vivant.com/en/showcompany/4724, Focal], on ''patrimoine-vivant.com''</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Guy HF cabinet-making becomes Focal Eb\u00e9nisterie Bourgogne.<ref>[http://larepubliqueduson.com/2016/02/12/focal-bourgogne-ebenisterie-le-berceau-dun-savoir-faire/ Focal Eb\u00e9nisterie Bourgogne, le berceau d\u2019un savoir-faire], sur ''larepubliqueduson.com''. Consult\u00e9 le 29 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n== Technologies ==\nFocal-JMlab maintains a regular research and development program in speaker drivers\u2019 technologies. Investments in this field have enabled the company to conceive various innovative concepts.<ref>[http://culturehd.com/focal-le-retour-de-la-vraie-enceinte-haute-fidelite_2322 Richard, FOCAL le retour de la vraie enceinte haute fid\u00e9lit\u00e9, on ''culturehd.com'']</ref> Ten innovations have been patented to date.\n\n=== Inverted dome tweeter (1981) ===\nAn inverted dome tweeter was designed and developed by Focal in 1981. (Inverted dome tweeters appeared at least as early as the late 1960s in the EPI 100 loudspeaker manufactured by EPI/Epicure. It had an inverted paper dome.) One of its main advantages is its low directionality and its high dynamics. The majority of the brand's tweeters still feature this technology.\n\n=== K2 cone (1986) ===\nIn 1986, the company introduced the Polykevlar sandwich structure. The Poly-K cone is composed of two layers of aramid fibres applied to either side of a hollow-micro-ball structure in order to improve the compromise between weight-rigidity-and damping.\n\n=== Polyglass cone (1988) ===\nPolyglass technology was introduced by Focal in 1988. This consists in depositing fine glass micro-balls on the surface of a cellulose pulp cone (paper). This combination of glass and paper results in a very rigid material with a low mass, providing excellent damping qualities. The Polyglass cone resulted in a very linear [[frequency response]] curve and improved the definition of the midrange.\n\n=== \"W\" sandwich cone (1995) ===\nIn 1995, Focal improved its sandwich concept with its \"W\" cone system which consists of two sheets of glass fibres applied to a structural foam core. Unlike the mono-material cones, the \"W\" sandwich cone optimises the frequency response curve by maximising the mass, rigidity and damping.\n\n=== Beryllium tweeter (2002) ===\nIn 2002, Focal launched another innovation to their product line, the [[Beryllium]] Tweeter, which was only the second time a tweeter had ever been manufactured from Beryllium. Yamaha had introduced the Beryllium tweeter and Beryllium mid-range speaker in the NS-1000 back in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thevintageknob.org/yamaha-NS-1000.html|title=Yamaha NS-1000 on thevintageknob.org|last=Dahl|first=Axel|website=www.thevintageknob.org|language=en|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref>\n\nBeryllium is seven times more rigid than titanium (six times more rigid than aluminum), but has the same mass. It enabled Focal to develop a lighter and faster tweeter which provides excellent damping qualities. When associated with the inverted dome concept, the frequency response can be increased to 40&nbsp;kHz, and more than 5 octaves can be spanned.\nBeing ten times more expensive than gold,Focal only uses the Beryllium Tweeter for the Premium ranges: Utopia, Sopra, Electra and high end studio monitors.\n\n=== Tweeter Al-Mg (2007) ===\nThis tweeter was introduced by Focal JMlab in 2007. The use of aluminium increases damping qualities, whereas the use of magnesium increases the rigidity of the dome. This enabled the frequency response of the Al-Mg Tweeter to be increased to 28&nbsp;kHz.\nThe Al-Mg Tweeter is used on the Chorus range of the Home line and on the CMS and Shape ranges of the Pro line, among others.\n\n=== Flax membrane cone (2013) ===\nEighteen years after introducing the \"W\" sandwich cones, Focal launched the new Made in France \"F\" Sandwich cone (for [[Flax]]). Composed of flax fibres enclosed in two thin layers of glass fibre, this solution offers a natural sound without colouration thanks to light, rigid and damped cones.<ref>[http://www.caraudiovideo.com/index.php/content/view/3454/57/ Alexandre, Focal d\u00e9voile une nouvelle membrane Flax \u00e0 base de lin, on ''caraudiovideo.com'']</ref>\n\n=== Tuned mass damper (2015) ===\nIn order to control resonance and to reduce medium speaker driver distortions, the Tuned Mass Damper technology consists of an additional mass that oscillates in opposition to the resonance frequency. The suspension is optimised to avoid distortions and increase the definition.<ref name=\"Sopra White Paper\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4419|title=Sopra White Paper, on ''focal.com''}}</ref>\n\n=== Infinite horn loading system (2015) ===\nThe rear of the Beryllium tweeter is loaded via a small cavity which is connected to the exterior of the enclosure by a horn. The inside is filled with a damping material. Rear wave of the tweeter is gradually absorbed to reduce distortion.<ref name=\"Sopra White Paper\"/>\n\n=== M-shaped inverted dome tweeter (2016) ===\nTweeters from the K2 Power, renewed in 2016, feature this M-shaped profile. This shape enables to extend the frequency response, a smoother diffusion, and more detailed treble.<ref>[http://www.autonews.fr/hi-tech/caraudiovideo-focal-k2-power-2016-61362 Focal renouvelle la l\u00e9gendaire ligne K2 Power], sur ''autonews.fr''. Consult\u00e9 le 29 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n=== M-profile cone (2018) ===\nUtopia M speaker drivers (range launched in 2018) feature a M-profile cone which combines rigidity, damping and lightness for more linear frequency response, reduced harmonic distortion and better sound dispersion.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marksparrow/2018/10/30/focal-unleashes-a-new-range-of-high-end-car-audio-speakers/ | title=Focal Unleashes a New Range of High-End Car Audio Speakers}}</ref>\n\n=== Slatefiber cone (2019) ===\nDeveloped with the Chora range, the Slatefiber cone is a membrane composed of recycled non-woven carbon fibres and thermoplastic polymer. Made in France at Focal, this \"slate effect\" cone provides a dynamic and rich sound. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marksparrow/2019/09/06/focal-unveils-its-brand-new-range-of-affordable-speakers-for-audiophiles/#586a421a5fe2 | title=Focal Unveils Its Brand New Range Of Affordable Speakers For Audiophiles}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nFocal-JMlab has organised its range of products into five universes: the Home line, the Car line, the Pro line for music industry professionals, the Headphones line since 2012 and finally the Integration line (public address sound systems)\n\nThe Home loudspeakers universe represents 59% of the company turnover and is divided into two collections:\n* '''Classic''': all the loudspeakers of this collection are designed, developed and manufactured in France and combine all the Focal technological innovations (inverted dome tweeter, \u00ab W \u00bb and \u00ab F \u00bb sandwich con, etc.). Among the principal products, there are the Utopia, Sopra, Electra, Aria, Chorus, Kanta and more recently Chora lines. In 2013, launches Easya, high-fidelity wireless loudspeakers connectable with multiple sources thanks to built-in ''Bluetooth''\u00ae aptX\u00ae technology.\n\nThe Grande Utopia is the collection's emblematic loudspeaker. The first generation of the Grande Utopia, born in 1995, is a condensation of all the expertise and experience that Focal had gained since its creation. The second generation, in 2002, had the particularity of featuring pure [[Beryllium]] dome tweeters which enable it to receive, the year after, the \"Golden Sound\" award in Japan.<ref>[http://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/le-fabricant-d-enceintes-acoustiques-focal-reorganise-sa-production.N7230 Le fabricant d'enceintes acoustiques Focal r\u00e9organise sa production ], on usinenouvelle.com, ''L'Usine nouvelle''</ref> The third generation, launched in 2008, was a concentration of the best of Focal technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307|title=Archives - Le Point.fr|first=Le Point|last=magazine|website=Le Point.fr|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610205119/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307|archive-date=2015-06-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> Designed by Pineau & Le Porcher, The Grande Utopia EM distinguished itself through its extraordinary dimensions: weighing 570&nbsp;lbs (260&nbsp;kg) and standing over 6&nbsp;ft (2m) high. The cabinets can be customised at the cabinet-making facility in [[Bourbon-Lancy]] which is in charge of manufacturing and finishing the cabinets. In 2018, Focal unveiled Grande Utopia EM Evo and Stella Utopia EM Evo, which feature the latest technology of the brand<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audioxpress.com/news/focal-adds-large-size-grande-utopia-em-evo-and-stella-utopia-em-evo-loudspeakers-to-its-utopia-range |title = Focal Adds Large Size Grande Utopia EM Evo and Stella Utopia EM Evo Loudspeakers to its Utopia Range}}</ref>.\n\n* '''New Media''': Since 2008, with the arrival of the D\u00f4me miniature loudspeaker (available with Flax cone since 2014),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalversus.com/home-cinema-speakers/focal-dome-flax-p21982/test.html|title=Les Num\u00e9riques - Test, actu, comparatif high-tech/\u00e9lectrom\u00e9nager|website=www.digitalversus.com}}</ref> Focal has adapted its know-how to new modes of music consumption with compact loudspeakers, \"Plug and Play\", multimedia and more recently wireless (XS Book Wireless in 2013). In 2013, Focal launched 5.1 Home Cinema Packs in the New Media collection. Since May 2014, Focal entered the soundbar market launching Dimension, a 5.1 soundbar which, associated with its subwoofer, can be used as a sound plate for a flat screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-releases-more-details-on-its-dimension-soundbarsoundbase-solution|title=Focal releases more details on its Dimension soundbar/soundbase solution|publisher=}}</ref>\nThe Sib line evolved in 2017 and became Sib Evo featuring [[Dolby Atmos]] technology.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-launches-sib-evo-dolby-atmos-speaker-package Focal launches Sib Evo Dolby Atmos speaker package], on ''whathifi.com''.</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1980s the Car Audio department was born and the first car audio products were launched. In 2010, the Car Audio division has been reorganized into three ranges and represents now 30% of the turnover.\n* '''Elite''' : manufactured in France, the Utopia Be and K2 Power kits enable made-to-measure installations. It is the high-end range of the Focal Car Audio offering. In June 2014, Focal launches the made in France, handmade high-end Ultima kit. This concentrates Focal technologies used in the Grande Utopia EM speaker and in the SM9 monitoring speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/utopia-be/511-ultima.html|title=Car Audio Kit Utopia Ultima - Focal|website=Focal}}</ref>. End of 2018, the Utopia M line joins the Elite range with a new \"\u00e0 la carte\" concept which enables to customers to configure their own system.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* '''Performance''' : products of this range offer the possibility of creating your own installation thanks to the technical solutions of the Expert, Access and Auditor lines.\n* '''Int\u00e9gration''' : This range offers simple and quick to install products, particularly \"Plug & Play\" kits intended for improving some brands\u2019 original acoustic ([[BMW]], [[Peugeot 207]] and [[Volkswagen Golf Mk6|Golf 6]], [[Renault]] and [[Toyota]]) but also the Universal line where each system has a reduced volume and is easy to install.\n\nIn 2002, a professional department, \"Focal Professional\" has been created, offering studio monitors dedicated to [[recording studio]]s. The range is composed of five lines: SM9, SM6, CMS, Shape and Alpha to which the Listen professional and Clear Professional headphones designed for sound professionals (sound engineers and musicians) were added in 2018<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audiomediainternational.com/new-gear/review-focal-clear-professional |title = Review: Focal Clear Professional}}</ref>. The range now represents 11% of the company turnover.\n\nSince 2007, Focal have offered invisible sound systems, In-Wall and In-Ceiling, in order to add sound to public and private places. In 2018, the brand presents 100 Series and 300 Series which include Outdoor loudspeakers<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/home-theater/focal-100-od6-100-od8-speaker-news/ | title=Rain or Shine, Take Your Tunes Outside with Focals's New Speaker Line| date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\nFinally, in 2012, Focal expanded into commercializing its first nomad headphone, Spirit One which is replaced by Spirit One S model two years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/evt/spiritones/|title=Spirit One S, on focal.com|publisher=|access-date=2014-06-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626122056/http://www.focal.com/evt/spiritones/|archive-date=2014-06-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> The range is completed in 2013 with the Spirit Classic, a headphone intended for a use at home and Spirit Professional. In 2015, Focal launches its very first in-ear headphones named Sphear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-unveils-sphear-in-ear-headphones|title=Focal unveils Sphear in-ear headphones|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn 2016, Focal launches two Made in France high-end headphones hand made in their factory, Elear ad Utopia.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-introduces-utopia-and-elear-high-end-headphones Focal introduces Utopia and Elear high-end headphones], on ''whathifi.com''</ref> Then, in 2017, the Collection is completed with Clear headphones<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://hometheaterhifi.com/reviews/headphone-earphone/focal-clear-headphones-review/ |title = Focal Clear Headphones Review|date = 2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\nThen, in 2017 marks the arrival of a complete line of mobile wired or wireless headphones. 5 models are now available: Listen, Listen Wireless, Spark, Spark Wireless and Sphear S.\nFocal launches its very first Made in France high-end closed-back headphones in 2018 with Elegia<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audioxpress.com/news/focal-introduces-elegia-high-end-closed-back-headphones |title = Focal Introduces Elegia High-End Closed-Back Headphones}}</ref> followed by Stellia in 2018 and a DAC and amplifier for headphones named Arche<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.innerfidelity.com/content/focal-announces-new-closed-back-stellia-headphone-arche-dacamp |title = Focal Announces New Closed-Back Stellia Headphone, Arche DAC/AMP }}</ref>.\n\n==Partnerships==\n\n===Automotive partnerships===\nIn 2016 and 2017, Focal collaborated with several French car manufacturers to equip production vehicles. First vehicle [[Peugeot]] 3008 SUV, 5008 SUV,508<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.motor1.com/news/235065/peugeot-508-first-edition/ |title = New Peugeot 508 First Edition Has All the Bells and Whistles}}</ref> and SUV 2008 then DS7 Crossback and DS3 Crossback<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.automotiveworld.com/news-releases/ds-3-crossback-icon-of-high-tech-style-2/ | title=DS 3 Crossback: Icon of high tech style &#124; Automotive World}}</ref>by [[DS Automobiles]] and finally the rebirth of the [[Alpine (automobile)|Alpine]] brand with the A110.\nFocal also participates in several concept cars of these brands such as E-Tense,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/citroen/2016-ds-e-tense-concept-ar172617.html | title=2016 DS E-Tense Concept @ Top Speed| date=2016-02-26}}</ref> X E-Tense, E-Legend,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/peugeot-e-legend-100-kwh-battery/ |title = Peugeot Presents Stunning e-LEGEND Concept with 100 KWH Battery}}</ref> etc.\n\n===Tournaire===\nFor the launch of its first high-end Made in France headphones, Focal introduced a piece of collection in collaboration with [[Philippe Tournaire|Tournaire]] jeweler. The Utopia headphones have been customized with the mark of the Trilogy, the symbol of Tournaire jewelers. They are made of 18-karat gold mounted with diamonds. Available in 8 pieces only.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-utopia-tournaire-are-worlds-most-expensive-headphones Focal Utopia by Tournaire are world's most expensive headphones], on ''whathifi.com''</ref>\n\n===Ubisoft===\nIn September 2017, Focal signed a partnership with [[Ubisoft]], French video games publisher. For the release of [[Assassin's Creed Origins]] game, Focal launched 2 headphones in limited editions: Listen Wireless and Utopia by Tournaire.<ref>[http://www.jeuxactu.com/assassin-s-creed-origins-focal-lance-2-casques-audio-dont-1-a-50-000-111390.htm, Assassin\u2019s Creed Origins : Focal lance 2 casques dont 1 \u00e0 50 000\u20ac] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117213552/http://www.jeuxactu.com/assassin-s-creed-origins-focal-lance-2-casques-audio-dont-1-a-50-000-111390.htm |date=2018-01-17 }}, sur '' jeuxactu.com. Consult\u00e9 le 30 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n== Figures ==\n\nFocal-JMlab's turnover for 2016 was \u20ac53 million, 70% of which came from exports.<ref>[http://www.capitalfi-carnet-rencontres.com/focal 1 rencontre tr\u00e8s haute fid\u00e9lit\u00e9 sur '''www.capitalfi-carnet-rencontres.com'']</ref>\n\nDistribution of turnover per continent in 2012:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.focal.com/presse/presskit_focal2013.pdf |title=2013 Focal Press Kit, sur ''focal.com'' |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112162639/http://www.focal.com/presse/presskit_focal2013.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Europe : 57%\n* America : 20%\n* Middle East and Africa:  2,5%\n* Asia/Oceania:  20,5%\n\nThe Focal brand is distributed in more than 160 countries worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/stores,|title=Focal Dealers sur ''focal.com''}}</ref>\n \nFocal-JMlab employs more than 230 people at its 187,292 ft2 (17,400m2) facility in Saint-\u00c9tienne,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> which regroups the production, R&D and management departments at the same site.\n\nVervent Audio Group posted a turnover of \u20ac110 million in 2019 and employed 430 people at that point.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Competitors ==\n'''Acoustic loudspeakers : '''\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n* [[Bowers & Wilkins]]\n* [[Cabasse (company)|Cabasse]]\n* [[KEF]]\n\n'''Headphones :'''\n* [[AKG Acoustics|AKG]]\n* [[Sennheiser]]\n* [[Sony]]\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n\n'''Car Audio : '''\n* Audison/Hertz\n* [[Harman International Industries|Harman Kardon]]\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n* [[Meridian Audio]]\n\n'''Professional equipment :'''\n* Adam\n* [[JBL (company)|JBL]]\n* [[Fostex]]\n* [[Yamaha]]\n\n[[List of studio monitor manufacturers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{official|http://www.focal.com/en }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Focal-Jmlab}}\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of France]]\n[[Category:Loudspeaker manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1979]]\n[[Category:French brands]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n|brands         = Focal\n|name           = Focal-JMLab\n|logo           = [[File:Logo Focal ListenBeyond Noir 280px.jpg|latest Focal logo]]\n|type           = \n|founder        = Jacques Mahul\n|foundation     = 1979\n|hq_location_city = [[Saint-Etienne]], [[France]]\n|key_people     = Jacques Mahul - chairman and managing director\n|industry       = [[Consumer electronics]]\n|products       = [[home audio]], [[mobile audio]], [[professional audio]]\n|parent         = Vervent Audio Group\n|revenue        = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 110 million <small>(2019<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web | url=https://stereo-magazine.com/article/change-of-ownership-at-focal-naim | title=Change of ownership at Focal-Naim| date=2019-11-11}}</ref>)\n|num_employees  = 230<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.whathifi.com/features/focal-and-naim-french-anglo-alliance-thats-paying-dividends | title=Home}}</ref>\n|assets         = Naxicap Partners, Aquasour\u00e7a, Garibaldi Participations, Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Managers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hifiplus.com/articles/audios-transfer-window/|title=Audio\u2019s transfer window|website=Hi-Fi+}}</ref>\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.focal.com}}\n}}\n[[file:Focal JM lab opal 19ti crop.jpg|thumb|Focal Opal 19ti]]\n'''Focal-JMlab''' is a French brand, which has been designing and selling high-fidelity audio systems since 1979. This [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]]-based company manufactures [[Loudspeaker enclosure|loudspeakers]] for the home, [[Loudspeaker|speaker drivers]] for automobiles, [[headphones]] and professional monitoring loudspeakers.\n\nThe Grande Utopia is the brand's emblematic loudspeaker, which earned the company its worldwide reputation.<ref>[http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 Jack English auditions the JMlab Grand Utopia loudspeaker] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202120/http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |date=2013-10-29 }}, on ''focal.com''.</ref> It is considered one of the best high-fidelity loudspeakers in the world.<ref>[http://www.on-mag.fr/index.php/topaudio/actualites-news/10943-top-44-des-meilleures-enceintes-acoustiques-audiophiles-de-tous-les-temps-par-audiophilereviewcom Pierre Stemmelin, Top 44 des meilleures enceintes acoustiques audiophiles de tous les temps], on ''on-mag.fr/index.php''.</ref><ref>[http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307 Val\u00e9rie Marchive, Grande Utopia EM, l\u2019enceinte de tous les superlatifs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610205119/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307 |date=2015-06-10 }}, on ''lepoint.fr''.</ref>\n\nFocal's industrial strategy concentrates on having full control over the entire production process, from the design and manufacturing of the speaker drivers to the assembly of the final product. Its products are entirely designed and developed in France, and most of the production is carried out at the factory in Saint-\u00c9tienne (France).\n\nFocal-JMlab generates a \u20ac53 million annual turnover and employs about 230 people<ref name=\"auto1\"/> at its facility in Saint-\u00c9tienne, which groups the production, R&D and management departments at the same site. Its export share is 70%.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1980s ===\nFocal-JMlab, a research office dedicated to acoustics was founded in 1979 in Paris by engineer, high-fidelity enthusiast and technology journalist Jacques Mahul.<ref>[http://www.lexpress.fr/informations/vie-economique_642117.html Philippe Bidalon, \u00ab Les 100 qui font bouger Saint-\u00c9tienne : Jacques Mahul \u00bb], on lexpress.fr, ''[[L'Express]]''</ref> He began making his first speaker drivers in a small workshop in Saint-Etienne, at a precision mechanics company, which belonged to his father. Whilst producing his speaker drivers, Jacques Mahul also launched his own range of loudspeakers under the brand JMlab. His first loudspeaker, the DB13, was a bookshelf loudspeaker, which produced volumes comparable to larger loudspeakers, particularly in bass frequencies. Initially, he only sold his product to acquaintances but the DB13 was soon launched on the market.\n\nIn the 1980s, the two brands became established. Focal focused on innovation, producing specialised products such as the polyglass \"V\" cone and polykevlar cone. The materials used on the [[tweeter]] evolved from glass fibres to [[Kevlar]], producing a more linear frequency response curve and a smoother and less piercing treble.\nAs for JMlab, the company went from being a manufacturer of small-and medium-sized loudspeakers to a manufacturer of veritable high-end models.\n\n=== 1990s ===\nThings rapidly began to pick up speed in 1990 with the arrival of G\u00e9rard Chr\u00e9tien, another high end high fidelity enthusiast and [[editor-in-chief]] of the magazine ''L\u2019Audiophile'' since 1977. Currently, he is the managing director and marketing director of Focal-JMlab. By adapting the company's products to the demands of the consumer, the brand soon earned its role as leader on the French loudspeaker market.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/focal-jmlab-le-son-chez-soi-et-au-volant.N34160|title=Focal-JMlab Le son, chez soi et au volant|journal=Usinenouvelle.com/|first=L'Usine|last=Nouvelle|date=19 June 2003}}</ref> The company's turnover increased from \u20ac9 million in 1992 to \u20ac26 million in 2000.<ref name=\"pr\u00e9sentation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4022|title=Pr\u00e9sentation Focal-JMlab 2011, on the company official website|publisher=|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIt was also in the early 1990s that the company implemented an export strategy for its loudspeakers across Europe, Southeast Asia and North America. The brand's reputation on the international stage was reinforced by various awards. The JMlab Vega model was voted \"Loudspeaker of the Year, 1992\" in Japan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audiomarketing.com.au/pdf/focal/history.pdf|title=History Focal, on audiomarketing.com|publisher=|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105154002/http://www.audiomarketing.com.au/pdf/focal/history.pdf|archive-date=2012-01-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 1996, the Grande Utopia model was praised by the international press.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |title=Jack English auditions the JMlab Grand Utopia loudspeaker, on ''Stereophile'' |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029202120/http://www.focal.com/fr/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4020 |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\nFrom 2002, production was relocated in Saint-Etienne where about three-quarters of production still takes place with the aim of equipping every loudspeaker with \"Made in France\" speaker drivers.\n\nIn 2003, the two brands were incorporated under the name Focal-JMlab for home products, before being renamed as just Focal in 2005 for all product sectors.\n\n2003 was also the year that the company began collaborating with Paris-based design agency Pineau & Le Porcher. By combining sound quality and aesthetics, this move made Focal-JMlab products lifestyle loudspeakers in their own right and also gave the company a brand signature. Thus, Focal and Pineau & Le Porcher worked in close collaboration to come up with a completely new design for various ranges: Profile and Electra (2005), Chorus (2006), Utopia (2008) and Dome (2009).<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/quand-le-design-permet-de-se-differencier.N118371|title=Quand le design permet de se diff\u00e9rencier|first=L'Usine|last=Nouvelle|date=October 1, 2009|via=www.usinenouvelle.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the company bought up the Guy HF cabinet-making facility located in Bourbon-Lancy, Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire.\n\n=== 2010s ===\nIn 2011, Focal-JMlab merged with [[Naim Audio|Naim Audio Limited]], the leading high-end electronics brand in the UK, which mainly designs and manufactures audio electronics. The new holding company, Vervent Audio Group, owns and manages the two brands. However, both brands remain independent with their own specific philosophies and their own respective ranges and products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.on-mag.fr/index.php/topaudio/actualites-news/10577-focal-et-naim-audio-annoncent-leur-fusion-au-sein-de-lentite-focal-a-co|title=Focal et Naim Audio annoncent leur fusion au sein de l'entit\u00e9 Focal & Co|first=Pierre|last=Stemmelin|website=www.on-mag.fr}}</ref>\n\nThe two companies began consolidating their activities in 2013, with their presence on a common stand at the High End Show in Munich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908090919/http://www.hificritic.com/downloads/Munich2013.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 8, 2013|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Focal adopted a new visual identity and finally, in 2012, built a showroom and a new auditorium at its site in Saint-\u00c9tienne.\n\nIn 2014, Focal&Naim Group was taken over by its management team, Naxicap Partners (major shareholder), Aquasourca and Garibaldi Participations. Jacques Mahul remains involved and becomes Focal-JMlab Vice-Pr\u00e9sident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hifiplus.com/articles/audios-transfer-window/,|title=Why a week of audio business upheaval might not be a bad thing, on ''www.hifiplus.com''}}</ref> The same year, Focal is recognized by the French state thanks to ''The Entreprise du Patrimoine Vivant'' (Living Heritage Company) label. A label delivered under the authority of the French Minister for Economy, Finances and Industry rewarding French firms for the excellence of their traditional and industrial skills<ref>[http://www.patrimoine-vivant.com/en/showcompany/4724, Focal], on ''patrimoine-vivant.com''</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Guy HF cabinet-making becomes Focal Eb\u00e9nisterie Bourgogne.<ref>[http://larepubliqueduson.com/2016/02/12/focal-bourgogne-ebenisterie-le-berceau-dun-savoir-faire/ Focal Eb\u00e9nisterie Bourgogne, le berceau d\u2019un savoir-faire], sur ''larepubliqueduson.com''. Consult\u00e9 le 29 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n== Technologies ==\nFocal-JMlab maintains a regular research and development program in speaker drivers\u2019 technologies. Investments in this field have enabled the company to conceive various innovative concepts.<ref>[http://culturehd.com/focal-le-retour-de-la-vraie-enceinte-haute-fidelite_2322 Richard, FOCAL le retour de la vraie enceinte haute fid\u00e9lit\u00e9, on ''culturehd.com'']</ref> Ten innovations have been patented to date.\n\n=== Inverted dome tweeter (1981) ===\nAn inverted dome tweeter was designed and developed by Focal in 1981. (Inverted dome tweeters appeared at least as early as the late 1960s in the EPI 100 loudspeaker manufactured by EPI/Epicure. It had an inverted paper dome.) One of its main advantages is its low directionality and its high dynamics. The majority of the brand's tweeters still feature this technology.\n\n=== K2 cone (1986) ===\nIn 1986, the company introduced the Polykevlar sandwich structure. The Poly-K cone is composed of two layers of aramid fibres applied to either side of a hollow-micro-ball structure in order to improve the compromise between weight-rigidity-and damping.\n\n=== Polyglass cone (1988) ===\nPolyglass technology was introduced by Focal in 1988. This consists in depositing fine glass micro-balls on the surface of a cellulose pulp cone (paper). This combination of glass and paper results in a very rigid material with a low mass, providing excellent damping qualities. The Polyglass cone resulted in a very linear [[frequency response]] curve and improved the definition of the midrange.\n\n=== \"W\" sandwich cone (1995) ===\nIn 1995, Focal improved its sandwich concept with its \"W\" cone system which consists of two sheets of glass fibres applied to a structural foam core. Unlike the mono-material cones, the \"W\" sandwich cone optimises the frequency response curve by maximising the mass, rigidity and damping.\n\n=== Beryllium tweeter (2002) ===\nIn 2002, Focal launched another innovation to their product line, the [[Beryllium]] Tweeter, which was only the second time a tweeter had ever been manufactured from Beryllium. Yamaha had introduced the Beryllium tweeter and Beryllium mid-range speaker in the NS-1000 back in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thevintageknob.org/yamaha-NS-1000.html|title=Yamaha NS-1000 on thevintageknob.org|last=Dahl|first=Axel|website=www.thevintageknob.org|language=en|access-date=2016-03-27}}</ref>\n\nBeryllium is seven times more rigid than titanium (six times more rigid than aluminum), but has the same mass. It enabled Focal to develop a lighter and faster tweeter which provides excellent damping qualities. When associated with the inverted dome concept, the frequency response can be increased to 40&nbsp;kHz, and more than 5 octaves can be spanned.\nBeing ten times more expensive than gold,Focal only uses the Beryllium Tweeter for the Premium ranges: Utopia, Sopra, Electra and high end studio monitors.\n\n=== Tweeter Al-Mg (2007) ===\nThis tweeter was introduced by Focal JMlab in 2007. The use of aluminium increases damping qualities, whereas the use of magnesium increases the rigidity of the dome. This enabled the frequency response of the Al-Mg Tweeter to be increased to 28&nbsp;kHz.\nThe Al-Mg Tweeter is used on the Chorus range of the Home line and on the CMS and Shape ranges of the Pro line, among others.\n\n=== Flax membrane cone (2013) ===\nEighteen years after introducing the \"W\" sandwich cones, Focal launched the new Made in France \"F\" Sandwich cone (for [[Flax]]). Composed of flax fibres enclosed in two thin layers of glass fibre, this solution offers a natural sound without colouration thanks to light, rigid and damped cones.<ref>[http://www.caraudiovideo.com/index.php/content/view/3454/57/ Alexandre, Focal d\u00e9voile une nouvelle membrane Flax \u00e0 base de lin, on ''caraudiovideo.com'']</ref>\n\n=== Tuned mass damper (2015) ===\nIn order to control resonance and to reduce medium speaker driver distortions, the Tuned Mass Damper technology consists of an additional mass that oscillates in opposition to the resonance frequency. The suspension is optimised to avoid distortions and increase the definition.<ref name=\"Sopra White Paper\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/index.php?controller=attachment&id_attachment=4419|title=Sopra White Paper, on ''focal.com''}}</ref>\n\n=== Infinite horn loading system (2015) ===\nThe rear of the Beryllium tweeter is loaded via a small cavity which is connected to the exterior of the enclosure by a horn. The inside is filled with a damping material. Rear wave of the tweeter is gradually absorbed to reduce distortion.<ref name=\"Sopra White Paper\"/>\n\n=== M-shaped inverted dome tweeter (2016) ===\nTweeters from the K2 Power, renewed in 2016, feature this M-shaped profile. This shape enables to extend the frequency response, a smoother diffusion, and more detailed treble.<ref>[http://www.autonews.fr/hi-tech/caraudiovideo-focal-k2-power-2016-61362 Focal renouvelle la l\u00e9gendaire ligne K2 Power], sur ''autonews.fr''. Consult\u00e9 le 29 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n=== M-profile cone (2018) ===\nUtopia M speaker drivers (range launched in 2018) feature a M-profile cone which combines rigidity, damping and lightness for more linear frequency response, reduced harmonic distortion and better sound dispersion.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marksparrow/2018/10/30/focal-unleashes-a-new-range-of-high-end-car-audio-speakers/ | title=Focal Unleashes a New Range of High-End Car Audio Speakers}}</ref>\n\n=== Slatefiber cone (2019) ===\nDeveloped with the Chora range, the Slatefiber cone is a membrane composed of recycled non-woven carbon fibres and thermoplastic polymer. Made in France at Focal, this \"slate effect\" cone provides a dynamic and rich sound. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marksparrow/2019/09/06/focal-unveils-its-brand-new-range-of-affordable-speakers-for-audiophiles/#586a421a5fe2 | title=Focal Unveils Its Brand New Range Of Affordable Speakers For Audiophiles}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nFocal-JMlab has organised its range of products into five universes: the Home line, the Car line, the Pro line for music industry professionals, the Headphones line since 2012 and finally the Integration line (public address sound systems)\n\nThe Home loudspeakers universe represents 59% of the company turnover and is divided into two collections:\n* '''Classic''': all the loudspeakers of this collection are designed, developed and manufactured in France and combine all the Focal technological innovations (inverted dome tweeter, \u00ab W \u00bb and \u00ab F \u00bb sandwich con, etc.). Among the principal products, there are the Utopia, Sopra, Electra, Aria, Chorus, Kanta and more recently Chora lines. In 2013, launches Easya, high-fidelity wireless loudspeakers connectable with multiple sources thanks to built-in ''Bluetooth''\u00ae aptX\u00ae technology.\n\nThe Grande Utopia is the collection's emblematic loudspeaker. The first generation of the Grande Utopia, born in 1995, is a condensation of all the expertise and experience that Focal had gained since its creation. The second generation, in 2002, had the particularity of featuring pure [[Beryllium]] dome tweeters which enable it to receive, the year after, the \"Golden Sound\" award in Japan.<ref>[http://www.usinenouvelle.com/article/le-fabricant-d-enceintes-acoustiques-focal-reorganise-sa-production.N7230 Le fabricant d'enceintes acoustiques Focal r\u00e9organise sa production ], on usinenouvelle.com, ''L'Usine nouvelle''</ref> The third generation, launched in 2008, was a concentration of the best of Focal technologies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307|title=Archives - Le Point.fr|first=Le Point|last=magazine|website=Le Point.fr|access-date=2013-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610205119/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2008-09-08/grande-utopia-em-l-enceinte-de-tous-les-superlatifs/1387/0/272307|archive-date=2015-06-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> Designed by Pineau & Le Porcher, The Grande Utopia EM distinguished itself through its extraordinary dimensions: weighing 570&nbsp;lbs (260&nbsp;kg) and standing over 6&nbsp;ft (2m) high. The cabinets can be customised at the cabinet-making facility in [[Bourbon-Lancy]] which is in charge of manufacturing and finishing the cabinets. In 2018, Focal unveiled Grande Utopia EM Evo and Stella Utopia EM Evo, which feature the latest technology of the brand<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audioxpress.com/news/focal-adds-large-size-grande-utopia-em-evo-and-stella-utopia-em-evo-loudspeakers-to-its-utopia-range |title = Focal Adds Large Size Grande Utopia EM Evo and Stella Utopia EM Evo Loudspeakers to its Utopia Range}}</ref>.\n\n* '''New Media''': Since 2008, with the arrival of the D\u00f4me miniature loudspeaker (available with Flax cone since 2014),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalversus.com/home-cinema-speakers/focal-dome-flax-p21982/test.html|title=Les Num\u00e9riques - Test, actu, comparatif high-tech/\u00e9lectrom\u00e9nager|website=www.digitalversus.com}}</ref> Focal has adapted its know-how to new modes of music consumption with compact loudspeakers, \"Plug and Play\", multimedia and more recently wireless (XS Book Wireless in 2013). In 2013, Focal launched 5.1 Home Cinema Packs in the New Media collection. Since May 2014, Focal entered the soundbar market launching Dimension, a 5.1 soundbar which, associated with its subwoofer, can be used as a sound plate for a flat screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-releases-more-details-on-its-dimension-soundbarsoundbase-solution|title=Focal releases more details on its Dimension soundbar/soundbase solution|publisher=}}</ref>\nThe Sib line evolved in 2017 and became Sib Evo featuring [[Dolby Atmos]] technology.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-launches-sib-evo-dolby-atmos-speaker-package Focal launches Sib Evo Dolby Atmos speaker package], on ''whathifi.com''.</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1980s the Car Audio department was born and the first car audio products were launched. In 2010, the Car Audio division has been reorganized into three ranges and represents now 30% of the turnover.\n* '''Elite''' : manufactured in France, the Utopia Be and K2 Power kits enable made-to-measure installations. It is the high-end range of the Focal Car Audio offering. In June 2014, Focal launches the made in France, handmade high-end Ultima kit. This concentrates Focal technologies used in the Grande Utopia EM speaker and in the SM9 monitoring speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/utopia-be/511-ultima.html|title=Car Audio Kit Utopia Ultima - Focal|website=Focal}}</ref>. End of 2018, the Utopia M line joins the Elite range with a new \"\u00e0 la carte\" concept which enables to customers to configure their own system.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* '''Performance''' : products of this range offer the possibility of creating your own installation thanks to the technical solutions of the Expert, Access and Auditor lines.\n* '''Int\u00e9gration''' : This range offers simple and quick to install products, particularly \"Plug & Play\" kits intended for improving some brands\u2019 original acoustic ([[BMW]], [[Peugeot 207]] and [[Volkswagen Golf Mk6|Golf 6]], [[Renault]] and [[Toyota]]) but also the Universal line where each system has a reduced volume and is easy to install.\n\nIn 2002, a professional department, \"Focal Professional\" has been created, offering studio monitors dedicated to [[recording studio]]s. The range is composed of five lines: SM9, SM6, CMS, Shape and Alpha to which the Listen professional and Clear Professional headphones designed for sound professionals (sound engineers and musicians) were added in 2018<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audiomediainternational.com/new-gear/review-focal-clear-professional |title = Review: Focal Clear Professional}}</ref>. The range now represents 11% of the company turnover.\n\nSince 2007, Focal have offered invisible sound systems, In-Wall and In-Ceiling, in order to add sound to public and private places. In 2018, the brand presents 100 Series and 300 Series which include Outdoor loudspeakers<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/home-theater/focal-100-od6-100-od8-speaker-news/ | title=Rain or Shine, Take Your Tunes Outside with Focals's New Speaker Line| date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\nFinally, in 2012, Focal expanded into commercializing its first nomad headphone, Spirit One which is replaced by Spirit One S model two years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/evt/spiritones/|title=Spirit One S, on focal.com|publisher=|access-date=2014-06-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626122056/http://www.focal.com/evt/spiritones/|archive-date=2014-06-26|url-status=dead}}</ref> The range is completed in 2013 with the Spirit Classic, a headphone intended for a use at home and Spirit Professional. In 2015, Focal launches its very first in-ear headphones named Sphear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-unveils-sphear-in-ear-headphones|title=Focal unveils Sphear in-ear headphones|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn 2016, Focal launches two Made in France high-end headphones hand made in their factory, Elear ad Utopia.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-introduces-utopia-and-elear-high-end-headphones Focal introduces Utopia and Elear high-end headphones], on ''whathifi.com''</ref> Then, in 2017, the Collection is completed with Clear headphones<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://hometheaterhifi.com/reviews/headphone-earphone/focal-clear-headphones-review/ |title = Focal Clear Headphones Review|date = 2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\nThen, in 2017 marks the arrival of a complete line of mobile wired or wireless headphones. 5 models are now available: Listen, Listen Wireless, Spark, Spark Wireless and Sphear S.\nFocal launches its very first Made in France high-end closed-back headphones in 2018 with Elegia<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.audioxpress.com/news/focal-introduces-elegia-high-end-closed-back-headphones |title = Focal Introduces Elegia High-End Closed-Back Headphones}}</ref> followed by Stellia in 2018 and a DAC and amplifier for headphones named Arche<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.innerfidelity.com/content/focal-announces-new-closed-back-stellia-headphone-arche-dacamp |title = Focal Announces New Closed-Back Stellia Headphone, Arche DAC/AMP }}</ref>.\n\n==Partnerships==\n\n===Automotive partnerships===\nIn 2016 and 2017, Focal collaborated with several French car manufacturers to equip production vehicles. First vehicle [[Peugeot]] 3008 SUV, 5008 SUV,508<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.motor1.com/news/235065/peugeot-508-first-edition/ |title = New Peugeot 508 First Edition Has All the Bells and Whistles}}</ref> and SUV 2008 then DS7 Crossback and DS3 Crossback<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.automotiveworld.com/news-releases/ds-3-crossback-icon-of-high-tech-style-2/ | title=DS 3 Crossback: Icon of high tech style &#124; Automotive World}}</ref>by [[DS Automobiles]] and finally the rebirth of the [[Alpine (automobile)|Alpine]] brand with the A110.\nFocal also participates in several concept cars of these brands such as E-Tense<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/citroen/2016-ds-e-tense-concept-ar172617.html | title=2016 DS E-Tense Concept @ Top Speed| date=2016-02-26}}</ref>, X E-Tense, E-Legend<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/peugeot-e-legend-100-kwh-battery/ |title = Peugeot Presents Stunning e-LEGEND Concept with 100 KWH Battery}}</ref>, etc.\n\n===Tournaire===\nFor the launch of its first high-end Made in France headphones, Focal introduced a piece of collection in collaboration with [[Philippe Tournaire|Tournaire]] jeweler. The Utopia headphones have been customized with the mark of the Trilogy, the symbol of Tournaire jewelers. They are made of 18-karat gold mounted with diamonds. Available in 8 pieces only.<ref>[https://www.whathifi.com/news/focal-utopia-tournaire-are-worlds-most-expensive-headphones Focal Utopia by Tournaire are world's most expensive headphones], on ''whathifi.com''</ref>\n\n===Ubisoft===\nIn September 2017, Focal signed a partnership with [[Ubisoft]], French video games publisher. For the release of [[Assassin's Creed Origins]] game, Focal launched 2 headphones in limited editions: Listen Wireless and Utopia by Tournaire.<ref>[http://www.jeuxactu.com/assassin-s-creed-origins-focal-lance-2-casques-audio-dont-1-a-50-000-111390.htm, Assassin\u2019s Creed Origins : Focal lance 2 casques dont 1 \u00e0 50 000\u20ac] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117213552/http://www.jeuxactu.com/assassin-s-creed-origins-focal-lance-2-casques-audio-dont-1-a-50-000-111390.htm |date=2018-01-17 }}, sur '' jeuxactu.com. Consult\u00e9 le 30 novembre 2017</ref>\n\n== Figures ==\n\nFocal-JMlab's turnover for 2016 was \u20ac53 million, 70% of which came from exports.<ref>[http://www.capitalfi-carnet-rencontres.com/focal 1 rencontre tr\u00e8s haute fid\u00e9lit\u00e9 sur '''www.capitalfi-carnet-rencontres.com'']</ref>\n\nDistribution of turnover per continent in 2012:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.focal.com/presse/presskit_focal2013.pdf |title=2013 Focal Press Kit, sur ''focal.com'' |access-date=2013-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112162639/http://www.focal.com/presse/presskit_focal2013.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Europe : 57%\n* America : 20%\n* Middle East and Africa:  2,5%\n* Asia/Oceania:  20,5%\n\nThe Focal brand is distributed in more than 160 countries worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focal.com/en/stores,|title=Focal Dealers sur ''focal.com''}}</ref>\n \nFocal-JMlab employs more than 230 people at its 187,292 ft2 (17,400m2) facility in Saint-\u00c9tienne,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> which regroups the production, R&D and management departments at the same site.\n\nVervent Audio Group posted a turnover of \u20ac110 million in 2019 and employed 430 people at that point.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Competitors ==\n'''Acoustic loudspeakers : '''\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n* [[Bowers & Wilkins]]\n* [[Cabasse (company)|Cabasse]]\n* [[KEF]]\n\n'''Headphones :'''\n* [[AKG Acoustics|AKG]]\n* [[Sennheiser]]\n* [[Sony]]\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n\n'''Car Audio : '''\n* Audison/Hertz\n* [[Harman International Industries|Harman Kardon]]\n* [[Bang & Olufsen]]\n* [[Meridian Audio]]\n\n'''Professional equipment :'''\n* Adam\n* [[JBL (company)|JBL]]\n* [[Fostex]]\n* [[Yamaha]]\n\n[[List of studio monitor manufacturers]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.focal.com/en Official website]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n{{commons category|Focal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Focal-Jmlab}}\n[[Category:Audio equipment manufacturers of France]]\n[[Category:Loudspeaker manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1979]]\n[[Category:French brands]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "References section above external link section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focal-JMLab"}
{"title_page": "Varun Grover (writer)", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|1|26}}\n| birth_place         = [[Sundernagar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], India\n| occupation         = [[Screenwriter]], [[lyricist]], [[Film director|director]], [[stand-up comedian]]\n| yearsactive        = 2004-Present\n| notable_works      = [[Masaan]], [[Udta Punjab]], [[Dum Laga Ke Haisha]], [[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| alma_mater         = \n| spouse             = \n}}\n\n'''Varun Grover''' (born 26 January 1980) is an Indian [[Intellectual|inker]]. He won the award for Best Lyricist at the 63rd [[National Film Awards]] in 2015.<ref name=\"63rdawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dff.nic.in/writereaddata/Winners_of_63rd_NFA_2015.pdf|title=63rd National Film Awards|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=13 February 2018|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pal|first1=Divya|title=National Award winning lyricist Varun Grover recalls initial reactions to 'Moh Moh Ke Dhaage'|url=http://www.news18.com/news/movies/bahut-achcha-hai-par-slow-hai-national-award-winning-lyricist-varun-grover-recalls-initial-reactions-to-moh-moh-ke-dhaage-1222145.html|accessdate=13 February 2018|date=28 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Varun Grover (Civil 2003) wins award as Best Lyricist at 63rd National Film Awards 2016|url=http://www.itbhuglobal.org/chronicle/archives/2016/03/varun_grover_ci_1.php|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nGrover was born in [[Sundernagar]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], to a school-teacher mother and army engineer father. His family is [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]].<ref>Akshay Manwani (24 July 2016), [https://scroll.in/reel/812351/varun-grover-interview-the-lack-of-respect-for-writers-stays-with-you-but-also-fuels-you \"Varun Grover interview: \u2018The lack of respect for writers stays with you, but also fuels you\u2019\"], ''[[Scroll.in]]''. Retrieved 20 March 2020.</ref> He spent his initial years in Sundernagar and [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]], before moving to [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]] for his adolescent years. He studied civil engineering at [[Indian Institute of Technology (BHU) Varanasi]], graduating in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/brutal-censors-give-another-route-to-creativity-masaan-writer-varun-grover/|title=Brutal censors give another route to creativity: \u2018Masaan\u2019 writer Varun Grover|date=2015-10-07|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Liberal in his thoughts |url=http://dailypost.in/lifestyle/fashion-and-beauty/52886-liberal-in-his-thoughts | agency=Daily Post India | accessdate=2015-11-25 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/92124/varun-grover-interview-comedy-songwriter-scrip-writer/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Varun Grover on His Journey, the Film Industry, & Sexism in Standup Comedy|date=2017-03-20|work=The Better India|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/VXp7QpToHxvptmcOU9ZCyH/Masaan-man-Varun-Grovers-journey-A-civil-engineer-turned-B.html|title=Masaan man Varun Grover\u2019s journey: A civil engineer turned Bollywood scriptwriter|last=Jha|first=Lata|date=2015-08-05|work=livemint.com|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/neeraj-ghaywan-varun-grover-to-donate-national-award-prize-money-to-farmers-2784161/|title=Neeraj Ghaywan, Varun Grover to donate National Award prize money to farmers|date=2016-05-04|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/VXp7QpToHxvptmcOU9ZCyH/Masaan-man-Varun-Grovers-journey-A-civil-engineer-turned-B.html|title=Masaan man Varun Grover\u2019s journey: A civil engineer turned Bollywood scriptwriter|first=Lata|last=Jha|date=5 August 2015|publisher=Mint}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/06/arts/television/sacred-games-netflix-review.html |title=Review: The Criminal Life in Mumbai in \u2018Sacred Games\u2019 |date=6 July 2018 |work=The New York Times |access-date=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/the-devil-of-the-details-5239759/ |title=Sacred Games review: The Devil of the Details |date=30 June 2018 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Collaboration in the Independent music space ==\nIn 2017 Varun Grover released Beete Dino Ke Geet<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/people-writer-comedian-varun-grover-discusses-new-collaboration-indie-space-lifestyle/18284165 |title=Indian music and cinema are tough nuts to crack: Varun Grover |website=mid-day.com |date=27 May 2017}}</ref> - a song in collaboration with US-based producer [[Krishna Chetan]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| ''[[Sandeep Aur Pinky Faraar]]'' || 2020 || Writer\n|-\n|''[[Sonchiriya]]''\n|2019\n| rowspan=\"8\" |Lyricist <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/sacred-games-makers-talk-about-their-favourite-character-criticism-and-first-pirated-show-in-reddit-ama-1826687.html|title='Sacred Games' Makers Talk About Their Favourite Character, Criticism, and First Pirated Show in Reddit AMA|work=News18|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Sui Dhaaga]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n|-\n| ''[[Kaala (2018 film)|Kaala]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Newton (film)|Newton]]'' || 2017 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/padmaavat-varun-grover-comedy-sanjay-leela-bhansali-deepika-padukone-karni-sena/191770|title=Before watching Padmaavat, check out comedian Varun Grover's hilarious take on the film|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Udta Punjab]]'' \n|rowspan=\"4\"|2016 <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-varun-grover-lyricist-of-many-phantom-films-slams-vikas-bahl-for-sexually-abusing-a-female-employee-2396304|title=Varun Grover, lyricist of many Phantom films, SLAMS Vikas Bahl for sexually abusing a female employee!|date=2017-04-11|work=dna|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Raman Raghav 2.0]]''<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Fan (film)|Fan]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Zubaan]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Fly Away Solo|Masaan]]'' \n|rowspan=\"3\"|2015 || Writer, Lyricist<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/brutal-censors-give-another-route-to-creativity-masaan-writer-varun-grover/|title=Brutal censors give another route to creativity: \u2018Masaan\u2019 writer Varun Grover|date=2015-10-07|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Bombay Velvet]]'' || Acting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/suprateek-chatterjee/yes-bombay-velvet-is-pret_b_7291322.html|title=Yes, 'Bombay Velvet' Is Pretty Atrocious, But We Should Not Be Happy About It|date=15 May 2015|publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Dum Laga Ke Haisha]]''\n|rowspan=\"8\"|Lyricist<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/loved-the-simplicity-of-tu-kisi-rail-si-varun-grover/|title=Loved the simplicity of \u2018Tu kisi rail si\u2026\u2019: Varun Grover|date=2015-08-06|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Ankhon Dekhi]]'' \n|rowspan=\"2\"|2014 <ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Katiyabaaz]]''<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Prague (2013 film)|Prague]]'' || 2013 <ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Gangs of Wasseypur \u2013 Part 2]]'' \n|rowspan=\"3\"|2012 <ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Gangs of Wasseypur \u2013 Part 1]]''<ref name=\":2\